First sentance: I don't think he ever made that distinction in his argument.  His argument is: death is good, the death of the human race in its entirety is ideal, the death of any less than that just doesn't matter.  In his mind, all this is true.  Humans ARE a pox on this planet, there's no talking/denying our way out of this.<br>
<br>
Second paragraph: Telling him to go die will do nothing, making it sound like he wants to go die and take any less than the rest of the population with him is fallacy.  His ideals would NOT be accomplished if he took 500 people out into the woods and died after some mass-orgy, so why should he?  How is he not standing up for what he believes in?  He's sustaining his original argument in the midst of the flames of his peers, he's explained his beliefs through various analogies and attempted to defend them against scrutiny, that IS standing up for your beliefs.<br>
<br>
Third paragraph: Who's to say that tomorrow we won't dry up another lake, or eradicate another species, or deforest another country?  What's more likely to happen?  The human race finds a cure for all it's plagues upon the world, or it throws another log on the fire?  How do you know you haven't met somone who's been reincarnated?  Who's to say you yourself haven't been reincarnated?<br>
<br>
re·in·car·na·tion   Pronunciation Key  (rn-kär-nshn)<br>
n. <br>
1-Rebirth of the soul in another body. <br>
2-A reappearance or revitalization in another form; a new embodiment: “The brownstone had already endured one reincarnation: In the 1940's, it was converted into eight studio apartments” (Ben Lloyd). <br>
<br>
As for wiping the earth of humans having some impact on reincarnation, how do you figure?  The belief of reincarnation is not that you always come back as another human, you may be a dog, or a cow, or a lemming, or a gnome.  In fact, I believe it's Hinduism that teaches: your actions in this life determine the state of your reincarnation, if you are a dork...you may come back as a mosquito or something.<br>
<br>
Fourth paragraph: MAYBE just maybe think about letting the earth be and allowing all humans to die off or something.<br>
<br>
Anyways, if you're still reading, take up a new hobby.  This whole post isn't anything personal, nor do I necessarily agree with any of the posted stances.  However, your whole attempt to discredit his beliefs was based on weak argument, and rather misleading (to yourself and to others) my sole intention in this post is the hope that people will examine what he said before jumping on the shit-slinging bandwagon.  He NEVER said he thought what happened to the people from sept. 11th was good, he NEVER said they deserved it, and in fact, he flamed the people who did it and who commit similar atrocities.  <br>
